groups, even as the friction among them often erupts into violence. Beauregard offers no simple solutions or proposed remedies for these contradictions; indeed, he doesn’t necessarily hold that they need to be resolved, since they are generative of city life. Without these four tensions, cities wouldn’t be cities. Rather, Beauregard argues that only by recognizing these ambiguities and contradictions can we even begin to understand our moral obligations, as well as the clearest paths toward equality, justice, and peace in urban settings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCities and townsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aCities and townsxPolitical aspects. 0aCities and townsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCities and townsxSocial aspects. 0aCities and towns. 0aUrban economics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aUS cities.  acontradictions.  adaily life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978022653524140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226535418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226535418/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles